[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(6) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And came unto them to Troas in five days.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The voyage from Troas to Philippi (see Notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 16:11-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") had taken only three days, but the ship had now to contend against the south-west current that set in from the Dardanelles, and probably also against the Etesian winds blowing from the north-east that prevail in the Archipelago in the spring.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Where we abode seven days.—It lies on the surface that the motive for this stay was to keep the Lord’s day (the name was probably already current; see Revelation 1:10), and to partake with the Church of what, even before the date of this journey, St. Paul had already spoken of as the Lord’s Supper (1Corinthians 11:20).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Where we abode seven days.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—It lies on the surface that the motive for this stay was to keep the Lord’s day (the name was probably already current; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 1:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and to partake with the Church of what, even before the date of this journey, St. Paul had already spoken of as the Lord’s Supper (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Corinthians 11:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "20:1-6 Tumults or opposition may constrain a Christian to remove from his station or alter his purpose, but his work and his pleasure will be the same, wherever he goes. Paul thought it worth while to bestow five days in going to Troas, though it was but for seven days' stay there; but he knew, and so should we, how to redeem even journeying time, and to make it turn to some good account.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After the days of unleavened bread - After the seven days of the Passover, during which they ate only unleavened bread. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In five days - They crossed the Aegean Sea. Paul, when he crossed it on a former occasion, did it in two days Acts 16:11-12; but the navigation of the sea is uncertain, and they were now probably hindered by contrary winds. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "In five days - They crossed the Aegean Sea. Paul, when he crossed it on a former occasion, did it in two days ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 16:11-12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; but the navigation of the sea is uncertain, and they were now probably hindered by contrary winds. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "6. And we sailed … from Philippi after the days of unleavened bread—(that is, the Passover). This, compared with 1Co 16:8, shows that the three months spent at Corinth (Ac 20:3) were the winter months.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "came … to Troas—for the third and last time. (See on [2073]Ac 16:8 and [2074]Ac 20:1).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in the five days—As it might have been done in two days, the wind must have been adverse. The vivid style of one now present will be here again observed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "where we abode seven days—that is, arriving on a Monday, they stayed over the Jewish sabbath and the Lord's Day following; Paul occupying himself, doubtless, in refreshing and strengthening fellowship with the brethren during the interval.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "From Philippi; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " where they embarked, and sailed on the river first, then on the sea. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "After the days of unleavened bread; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " though St. Paul would not have the Gentile converts to be burdened with the ceremonial law, yet, that he might not offend the Jews, for a while he complied with their rites, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 18:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 18:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", they being indeed dead, but not yet deadly; and therefore he stays his journey all the time of the passover solemnity, instructing them in the mean while of the nature and use of such things. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And we sailed away from Philippi,.... Which was in Macedonia, from whence they came in a straight course by Samothracia, over the Hellespont, to Troas, where the above six persons were waiting for them: and they set sail ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "after the days of unleavened bread; or the passover; which is mentioned only to observe the time of year when this voyage was taken; and not to suggest to us that Paul and his company stayed at Philippi, and kept this feast there; for the passover was only kept at Jerusalem, and besides was now abolished, and not to be observed by Christians: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and came unto them to Troas in five days; not that they were five days sailing from Philippi to Troas; but either they were so long in all, from their first setting out into Asia, to their arrival at Troas; or rather, they came to Troas within five days after the above six persons had got thither; so that they waited at Troas but five days for the apostle, and those that accompanied him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Where we abode seven days; by what follows they came into Troas on the Lord's day evening, or early on Monday morning, and stayed there till the next Lord's day, or first day of the week; for it follows, ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Where we abode seven days; by what follows they came into Troas on the Lord's day evening, or early on Monday morning, and stayed there till the next Lord's day, or first day of the week; for it follows, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
